# Commit & PR Rules

Follow these rules strictly when generating commit messages or PR descriptions.

## Commit Message Convention

All commits **must** follow [Conventional Commits v1.0.0](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/).

### Format

```
<type>[optional scope]: <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

### Types

| Type       | When to use                                              | Release effect  |
| ---------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | --------------- |
| `feat`     | New feature or capability                                | minor bump      |
| `fix`      | Bug fix                                                  | patch bump      |
| `perf`     | Performance improvement                                  | patch bump      |
| `revert`   | Reverts a previous commit                                | patch bump      |
| `docs`     | Documentation only                                       | no release      |
| `style`    | Formatting, whitespace â€” no logic change                 | no release      |
| `refactor` | Code restructure without feature or fix                  | no release      |
| `test`     | Adding or updating tests                                 | no release      |
| `chore`    | Tooling, config, dependency updates                      | no release      |
| `ci`       | CI/CD pipeline changes                                   | no release      |
| `build`    | Build system changes                                     | no release      |

### Breaking Changes

Append `!` after the type/scope, or add `BREAKING CHANGE: <description>` in the footer.
Both trigger a **major** version bump.

```
feat!: remove deprecated install command

BREAKING CHANGE: the `install` command has been removed; use `init` instead.
```

### Rules
- Description is lowercase, imperative mood, no trailing period
- Scope is optional; use it when the change is clearly scoped (e.g., `feat(cursor): ...`)
- Body and footer are optional; use them for context or breaking change notes
- One logical change per commit â€” do not batch unrelated changes

### Examples

```
feat(claude): add commit-and-pr rules
fix: resolve postinstall crash when config is missing
chore: bump cac to 6.7.14
docs: update README with init flags
feat!: rename config key from "enabled" to "tools"
```

## PR Message Generation

### Branch Rules
- **Always fetch and diff against the remote origin branch**, never a local branch.
- Before generating a PR description, run:
  ```bash
  git fetch origin
  ```
- Use `origin/<base>` as the base for the diff â€” never a bare branch name:
  ```bash
  git log origin/<base>..origin/<head> --oneline
  git diff origin/<base>...origin/<head>
  ```
- If the head branch has not been pushed to origin, stop and ask the user to push first.

### PR Description Structure

```markdown
## Summary
- <bullet: what changed and why>

## Type of change
- [ ] Bug fix (patch)
- [ ] New feature (minor)
- [ ] Breaking change (major)
- [ ] Docs / chore / refactor (no release)

## Test plan
- <what to verify manually or via CI>
```

### Target Branch Rules

| Source branch  | PR target  | Release outcome                     |
| -------------- | ---------- | ----------------------------------- |
| `feature/*`    | `develop`  | Beta pre-release (GitHub only)      |
| `fix/*`        | `develop`  | Beta pre-release (GitHub only)      |
| `develop`      | `main`     | Stable release â†’ published to npm   |
| `hotfix/*`     | `main`     | Stable release â†’ published to npm   |

## Branch & Release Strategy

This repo uses **semantic-release** with two long-lived branches:

| Branch    | Channel | npm publish | Tag format      |
| --------- | ------- | ----------- | --------------- |
| `main`    | stable  | yes         | `v1.2.3`        |
| `develop` | beta    | no          | `v1.2.3-beta.1` |

- Merges into `develop` trigger a GitHub pre-release tagged as beta â€” **not published to npm**.
- Merges into `main` trigger a stable GitHub release and publish to npm (GitHub Packages).
- Version bumps are driven entirely by commit types â€” do not manually edit the version in `package.json`.
